From: Cristian <pcristian292@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] en75_bmt: override mtd->_block_isbad so UBI doesn't depend on raw OOB[0..1]

The en75_bmt driver shrinks the user-visible MTD size by the BBT entries in
get_mapping_block_bbt(), so any block accessible through the visible MTD is,
by construction, not in the BBT — i.e., good. However, mtd_block_isbad()
falls through mtk_bmt_block_isbad() to spinand_mtd_block_isbad() which reads
OOB[0..1] raw and treats any non-0xFF byte as a factory-bad marker.

This breaks UBI persistence on NAND that has been written to before:
- UBI's writes don't touch OOB[0..1] directly, but residue from prior
  firmware images, mtd_block_markbad() calls from upper layers, or stale
  data from OEM stock can leave non-0xFF bytes there.
- Re-reading via spinand_isbad() sees those bytes and returns BAD.
- nanddev's in-RAM BBT cache makes the result sticky for the boot session.
- UBI ends up with most/all PEBs of an in-use partition flagged bad, and
  cannot find its volumes ("empty MTD device detected").

Fix: install a no-op _block_isbad on mtd in pub_init() after the size shrink.
The BBT's role was already fulfilled by shrinking mtd->size. UBI handles
runtime bad-PEB management itself via CONFIG_MTD_UBI_BEB_LIMIT.

Tested on TP-Link Archer XR500v (EN751221 + GD5F1GQ4xA SPI-NAND): without
this patch, ubi attach reports 96 of 104 PEBs as bad after one UBIFS write.
With the patch, ubi attach is stable across reboots and rootfs_data UBIFS
overlay survives sysupgrade-equivalent flashes of slot B.

--- a/drivers/mtd/nand/en75_bmt.c
+++ b/drivers/mtd/nand/en75_bmt.c
@@ -1361,12 +1361,33 @@ static int w_init(struct en75_bmt_m *ctx, struct device_node *np)

 static struct en75_bmt_m en75_bmt_m;

+/*
+ * UBI persistence depends on mtd_block_isbad() not lying about good blocks.
+ * The default chain mtk_bmt_block_isbad -> spinand_mtd_block_isbad reads
+ * OOB[0..1] raw and returns BAD for any non-0xFF, which mis-flags blocks
+ * whose OOB carries residue from prior writes, even though the block itself
+ * is healthy. en75_bmt has already excluded all factory-bad blocks from the
+ * visible MTD size via get_mapping_block_bbt()'s shift; any block reachable
+ * through the MTD is good by construction. So return 0 unconditionally.
+ * UBI's own per-PEB tracking (CONFIG_MTD_UBI_BEB_LIMIT) handles runtime
+ * wear-out without needing the OOB-based discriminator.
+ */
+static int en75_block_isbad(struct mtd_info *mtd, loff_t ofs)
+{
+	if (ofs < 0 || ofs >= mtd->size)
+		return 1;
+	return 0;
+}
+
 static int pub_init(struct device_node *np)
 {
 	int ret;

 	ret = w_init(&en75_bmt_m, np);
-	if (!ret)
+	if (!ret) {
 		w_sync_tables(&en75_bmt_m);
+		/* See comment on en75_block_isbad above. */
+		en75_bmt_m.mtk->mtd->_block_isbad = en75_block_isbad;
+	}
 	return ret;
 }

